1. Older nominative form: "magi". "mågå" was originally the accusative, and this form was then generalized and replaced the nominative.
2. "Mågå" is mostly used about the "inner" belly, the stomach. Cf. "mågå", a verb meaning "able to eat", or "mågå-siuok" (belly-sick) meaning "having a stomach disease".

"Kwið" is more commonly used about the "outer", visible part of the belly, e.g. "kwiðun" (belly.ADJ) means "having a big belly". It can, however, also be used in compounds like "kwið-riv" (belly-scratch) meaning "stomach-pain".

1. "Stur" is commonly used as an intensifier, e.g. "stur-guoð" (big-good) meaning "very good/tasty", "stur-faingen" (big-happy) meaning "very happy (about sth.)", "stur-graina" (big-to.cry) meaning "to cry a lot".
2. "Stur" is also common in lexified compounds, with a close equivalence in English "big": "stur-ton" (big-toe), "stur-bruor" (big-brother).

The working IELex2 definitions (as of 13.10.2015) give 'rotten' as "Most generic adjective for decomposing or decomposed solid food, typically fruit."  Two words in Latin satisfy this definition: (1) putridus 'rotten, decaying', from the stative verb putreō 'to be in a state of decay'; and (2) pūtidus 'rotting, decaying' from the intransitive verb puteō 'to rot, decompose'.  Pūtidus has a number of further figurative uses (moral sense, etc.), while putridus is only used properly of decaying things (OLD considers boats, teeth, etc.).  On these grounds I would suppose putridus to be the more basic term, however I will leave this open to consideration by others checking the Latin list.

Cf. Working definition for "at" in IELex 2 guidelines: "Specific location relative to some sort of scale, frame or other position: at (end, top). At a point, not a line or boundary. Not specifically by or alongside. Not specifically on (top) of, superposition. Not specifically in(side) a container – see entry for IN. As generic as possible." Cf. /lexeme/18791/ 'in, within'

Cf. working definition for 'in' in IELex 2 guidelines: "Location relative to a containing location, (any point) within. Not specifically inside, not necessarily something closed at the top Most generic meaning. Not movement in(to), stative location in. It is plausible that a given language will have more than one word to express the location 'in' and that the use of these words will be conditioned by a variety of factors, thus this is a difficult lexeme to elicit comprehensively."  ἐν satisfies the general locative sense 'in, within' when construed with the dative.

Basic meaning 'on account of, in consideration of'.  Becomes secondarily generalised as 'because' from frequent collocation as postposition with G.sg. relative pronoun οὗ ἔνεκα (univerbated οὕνεκα) 'on account of which, because'.

Principal use is as the intensive, not personal pronoun.  As an anaphoric pronoun it is only used independently and the oblique cases.  In the nominative forms, οὗτος, αὗτη, τοῦτο /lexeme/35438/ are used.
Not the most general 3rd person pronoun.  Has deictic reference 'the person there, that person'.

Also most generic demonstrative 'this' /lexeme/18965/.  This is the usual 3.sg. pronoun used in the nominative case.  For the oblique cases specific independent third person singular forms do exist, but these exist (G. οὗ, D. οἷ, A. ἕ), but these are not the most regular forms used in Attic prose.  Cf. H.W. Smyth & G. Messing (1956). Greek Grammar (Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press)  §325d.  Normally the anaphoric/intensive pronoun αὐτός /lexeme/18762/ is used in this sense in the oblique cases.
Also most generic third person singular pronoun 'he (she, it)' /lexeme/35438/.  See comments on the Ancient Greek system of deictic reference there.
Plural forms do have their own form unmarked form σφεῖς, but are not the most common 3.pl. pronouns in Attic prose. More normally αὐτός /lexeme/18762/ is used.
Basic meaning is 'use customarily, practice'.  The meanings 'acknowledge, consider as, believe' as cognative processes are secondary (and do not fit not the Swadesh term 'think').
Generally agreed to be identical with δέξιος 'right(side); fortunate' (as a personal name Δέξιος in Classical Attic cf. IG I³ 1032.429, etc.)
Unclear whether the form is δύο [dúo] or δύω [dúo̞ː] due to the lack of distinction of vowel length written in the Linear B script.  (Both forms are found in Classical dialects.)

This is the Swadesh term for tree-bark.  It is a learned re-introduction into the  from Ancient Greek.  The inherited form of the stem has survived in /lexeme/35592/ 'rind,peel; bark', but that word is not the Swadesh term.  See notes in the cognate class.
Not the most general term used in this sense.
Used of expansion of bodies of liquid and gas (e.g. expansion of balloons, swelling of waves).

Used for swelling of bodily tissue.  Active voice πρήζω can be used transitively 'to cause swelling', e.g. Tου ΄δωσε μια γροθιά και του ΄πρηξε το μάτι. 'He gave a punch and it swelled my eye.'  Passive voice as listed in the source form simply means 'to swell', e.g. Tο δόντι της είναι πρησμένο 'her tooth is swollen'.
Only rarely used in the sense of 'earth, soil'

Properly means 'foot' from the ankle downwards, but can also mean generally 'leg along with the foot', as χείρ 'hand' may also occasionally refer to the arm along with the hand.  These senses have been generalised later on in the language as in Modern Greek πόδι 'foot' /lexeme/7537/, 'leg' /lexeme/7569/, and χερί /lexeme/7547/ 'hand; arm'.

Properly means 'hand', but can also mean generally 'arm'.  Cf. ποῦς 'foot' /lexeme/18740/, which particularly means 'foot' from the ankle downwards, but can also mean generally 'leg along with the foot'.  These senses have been generalised later on in the language as in Modern Greek πόδι 'foot' /lexeme/7537/, 'leg' /lexeme/7569/, and χερί /lexeme/7547/ 'hand; arm'.
Only as anaphoric pronoun in oblique cases.
Primarily in sense 'seed (of plants)' but secondarily of animals 'seed, semen'.
Not the correct term (abnormal bodily swelling preferred Swadesh term).
General verb used of bipedal locomotion.
Typically used to describe the appearance of lightning and fire.
Old Attic has alternative form ξύν [ksýn].
'with' not the most basic meaning of this preposition
Cf. compound forms e.g. ἀπ-ομόργνῡμι 'wipe away, wipe clean', ἐξ-ομόργνῡμι 'wipe off from', ἐν-ομόργνῡμι 'wipe on(to)', etc.

This verb means to squeeze things (generally) in the sense of to apply pressure with the hands.  A different verb στύβω is used specifically for the squeezing of liquids out of anything (e.g. oranges, [insert name of local fruit], etc.).
More generally means 'the entirety of (a single thing)' emphasising magnitude.

Used of persons 'grown up, full-grown, mature'; of living creatures and inanimate objects 'of considerable size, large, tall'; generally 'great in amount or numbers, ample'; of emotions, actions 'great in degree, intensity, extreme'
Not the most general word used for 'black'.  The term is used emotively used, especially by poets, and the semantics overlap much with terms such as 'dark', 'funereal', 'ill-omened', etc.
to destroy or consume by fire, burn, burn alive (as a form of execution), offer as a burnt offering, to cremate (a corpse)
puer may be used when gender is unspecified, however the specific term puella exists for 'female child, girl'.  As an unspecified plural can mean 'children' (including girls).
'To approach and be present and be present, come.'

1. (of a weapon or tool) Blunt. 2. (of a light) Lacking brilliance, dull; (of a voice) hoarse, husky, thick. 3 (of the senses, faculties, etc.) Dull, dim; (of persons, utterances) Obtuse; (of actions) lacking in refinement, blunt.
May be used intransitively in sense of 'be afraid' or transitively take an accusative object of the object feared.

Hemolc'h, emolc'h is attested only twice in Middle Breton, both attestations occur in the Catholicon (1499), where the word is glossed 'chacier, Lat. uenari'. For the simplex helc'hiñ, GIB (1189) gives only one attestation from the 18th century with the meaning 'to tire, to exhaust'.
Gives further examples for hemolc'hiñ from the Early Modern and Modern periods (but none at all for helc'hiñ - still incomplete?).
Used with indicative, "introducing the protasis of an open condition, where the assumption is neither affirmed nor denied"

Most generally used to describe sharp features, such as bright or vivid colours, strong, bitter, or acidic tastes, keenness or acuteness of mental faculties, pointed enthusiasm, harshness or bitterness.
Not most common word used in this sense.
Singular intestīnum refers to the alimentary canal, but plural intestīna refers to the intestines or non-specifically 'guts' in particular.
Not the most basic term used in this sense.  Has shades of intensive meaning including 'tear apart, rend'.
Cf. related terms pertaining to the taking of auspices: auie, aviekate, aviekla .

The Leiden school of Indo-European reconstruction typically interprets this noun as an i-stem noun to a putative root *h₂eu̯- (cf. de Vaan [2008] Etymological Dictionary of Latin and the Other Italic Languages, Leiden: Brill, s.v. avis).  Alternatively this noun has been interpreted as a root-noun *h₂eu̯i- with final *-i- as part of the root itself (cf. Jochem Schindler [1969] "Die idg. Wörter für "Vogel" und "Ei" Die Sprache 15:144-167).
Not to be confused with words like θηλάζω (also often with compounded prefixes) meaning specifically 'to suckle (an infant)' (cf. θηλή 'teat, nipple').

The Mycenaean form is still an m-stem < PIE *sem-ei̯. (In later Greek the stem has been generalised as a n-stem in analogy with the general sound change of *m > n in word final position.) The Mycenaean form also attests the original consonant-stem D.sg. ending *-ei̯. (In first-millennium Ancient Greek the consonant-stem D.sg. morpheme has syncretised with the L.sg. morpheme *-i in all dialects). Cf. Ancient Greek D.sg.m. ἑνί.
Not the Swadesh Term.  Φλούδα is more generic than φλοιός and may refer to the skin or rind of trees and plants, including the skins of fruit.
Seems rather to refer to SURFACE than to MATERIAL (cf., e.g. Երկիր պագանել erkir paganel lit. "to kiss the earth", i.e. 'prostrate oneself before someone; worship; adore')
Seems rather to refer to fruit as opposed to a vegetable, not fruit in the sense of 'produce' (see պտուղ ptowł).

Although Martirosyan (2010:449) specifically claims that մայրի mayri may be the generic term for 'forest', I believe that an argument can be made that the term was still marked vis-a-vis անտառ antar.  The usage of mayri is not unambiguous, but it may be understood to imply 'forest' as a source of wood (either specifically cedar or also not specified for kind). Cf. Deuteronomy 19:5 "and when a man goes into the forest (= մայրի mayri) with his friend to cut wood" or Psalms 131:6 "we found it in the fields of (the) wood (= մայրեաց mayreac)".
Rather specifically 'plain, even, flat, level' and hence by extension also 'uniform; alike'.
Rather specifically 'a fast wind', i.e. 'a storm, tempest, hurricane'
Arguably a "non-classical" form from a specific dialect contemporary with Classical Armenian.
Rather 'large, huge, enormous; vast', also specifically 'mighty; victorious'.
Rather specifically 'to take a walk; march', also 'to (be) change(d)'.
Rather 'to stretch, extend, hold out' hence by extension 'to throw, hurl, fling; shoot'.
Rather 'to shove; insert', frequently 'to throw' in a figurative or idiomatic usage.
Rather 'to untie, loosen; release; dispatch, send' hence 'to throw' in a figurative or idiomatic sense (e.g. with eyes as in "throw one's eyes on someone", i.e. 'to cast eyes on; ogle, stare', etc.).
Doesn't refer to age. Implies 'ancient, antique', also 'decayed, worn-out'.
Rather 'filthy, soiled; foul, unclean; polluted (say of air)'.
Identification of sie-/sia- (formerly considered a demonstrative) as numeral 'one' now agreed. Kloekhorsts assumption of original stem si- is doubtfuln (no syllabic spellings).
Given only in the appendix of words that were not confirmed by informants. So probably not Swadesh term.

Although the root nakt- may be more frequent than kṣap-, this follows only from the frequent use of adverbial náktam ʿin the nightʿ and the formula náktā uṣâsā ʿnight and dawnʿ. As a full noun, kṣap- is better attested, but not clearly better than râtrī-.
Nearly as frequent in the RV as kṣáp-, and clearly the default term in later Vedic.
Perhaps not the Swadesh term. The meaning seems to be rather intensive than neutral. CHECK
Less frequent than dāra-, and more often in compounds.

Etymologically it should be "the other one of two", but attestations appear to reveal a broader meaning.
ālthough Bailey glosses with ʿmanʿ, the basic meaning appears to be ʿhuman, personʿ̇: derived adjective means ʿhumanʿ, not ʿmale, manlyʿ.

Only attested in gloss "enc hehen da me?" BN lat. 11411 fo 102b. Fleuriot assumes the existence of Old Breton me.

In the gloss: rusc dar et rusk caerdin 'oak bark and bark of the rowan tree'. The Welsh cognate is rhisgyn, rhisglyn. Therefore, one expects *risc, not rusc. It was suggested that Breton rusc has been borrowed from Romance *rusca or that  was influenced by a Romance word. This Romance word is probably of Celtic origin. The vowel -u- is also found in Cornish.

tar glosses 'uentrem' (Berne ms 167, fo 47a, Georg. IV v. 122). tor* is only attested in the word toroc gl. 'gurgulio' for 'curculio' 'weevil'; cf. Modern Breton teureug, teurg 'tick', Welsh torogen 'toick, buck'. If toroc is derived from tor, the original meaning would be 'bellied insect'. (Alzernatie etymology for toroc by Ifor Williams).
For the correct assignment and interpretation of different forms, cf. Catt 2014
Nut the usual term any more; only in dual and changing meaning to 'hearing, understanding'
Occurs in a number of glosses and corresponds to Latin pectoris 'breast', carine 'hull', monte 'hill' (in place-names).

Forms attested in Old Breton: 1) Infinitive diminet 'to come' > *devenet > *devonet > Middle Breton *donet. 2) Finite form doit for *doith, i.e. 3sg. pret. 'came' < *tu-ag-t-. Glosses Latin sustullerit 'to take, to bring', a meaning also attested for this verb in Middle Breton.
Abaev gives "yssyn" as the form, although the most common written variant is "ssyn".
Check difference with liz- 'run away', waj- 'бегать'.
Supposed to be specifically front thigh, but is actually found with both. By far more frequent that aʁd in the corpus, although both are used by native speaker for the same stimuli.
Considerably less frequent than šin. Semantic differentiation is unclear, but šin is probably the basic term (cf. also pl. šin-tɜ 'thighs', but ɜʁd-tɜ is virtually nonexistent).

In: ni degurme(h) ni dimenu; quamvis sint montes bid it crin doiar. Meaning of context: The presence of mountains, forming a three-dimensional landscpe, does not change the round form of the earth. "Neither does (the relief) increase nor remove: although there were mountains, the earth is round."
In the place-name Caer lagat nos 'the house of the eye of the night' (Cartulary of Quimperlé 155-56).

In: treit controlion gl. antipodarum 'oppised feet'.
The attested form is plural. The singular *troit can however be postulated on the basis of Old Cornish truit 'foot' in the Vocabularium Cornicum.
In: dacr-lon 'full of tears', bod-lon 'full of satisfaction', cob-lon 'complete, perfect' (< *kom-lon).
In the compound da-gweithred 'good deed' and as first member of compounded personal names.
In the place-name mat uallis glossé 'bona uallis' and as first member of compound personal names.
euin gl. unguis 'fingernail'. Seems to be identical with eguin gl. adungem i.e. unguem?.
In derivation deuueticon gl. cremata 'burnt, burnt to ashes'. Plural of the verbal adjective  in -etic.

In: 1) guelt-oguat gl. fastigium 'place where grass grows'. 2) guelt-iocion gl. fenosa 'place where hay/grass grows'; plural of a  in -ioc derivationof guelt. 3) guelt-betiuou; guelt seems to mean 'pasture'.
In: is petguar blidan 'it is four years'.
Attested in a denominal verb: admosoi, 3sg. subj. pres. 'who would dirty' gl. inrogauerit maculam. Cf. Middel Breton mous 'excrement' (Ivonet Omnes).

In: siscuint homines super eum 'that men beat on him (so that he dies)'. -scuint seems to be the 3pl. pres. subj. of a verb with theroot sco, perhaps originally *scu. The first syllable si- is not a reduplication but rather a intensive prefix.
1) arimrot 3sg. pret. gl. functus est 'to execute, to practice' < *ari-ambi-ret 'to run around'. 2) retemdirot 1sg. pret. 'to try' < ro + (?tu-)ambi-dī-ret
In cic-guan gl. fuscina 'fork, meat-picker', lien-cic, lien-chig 'membrane, net of flesh'.
arimrot 3sg. pret. < *ari-ambi-ret 'to run around'. 2) rotemdirot 1. sg. pret. < ro + (?tu-)ambi-dī-ret 'to try'.
Apparently now less frequent than toxm in the meaning 'egg'

Aorist ávocat and perfect uvā́ca are used in suppletion to present brū-, so they are the Swadesh terms in these categories. I suggest removing the "exclude" mark, unless we decide not to count suppletive roots.
Attested only once in Middle Breton, in the Catholicon (1499).

First attestation in Quiquer, Nomenclator (1633) p. 20: squilfou 'arms, defences (of a boar)'. The meaning 'claw' is only attested from Early Modern Breton onwards, cf. Gregoire de Rostrenen, Dictionnaire François - Celtique 1732, p. 473: squilf 'claw, nail of animals, ...' squilfou al leon 'the claws of the lion', squilfou ar c'hazh 'the claws of the cat'.
Attested in the plural a bleuou gl. iubis 'by the hair/mane' and in the dervied adjective bleoc sg. gl. criniti 'hairy', bleocion gl. pilossos 'pilose'.
In the compound durn-le gl. capulo 'hilt of a sword', lit. 'fist/hand-place'.

1) lom-rod gl. dautus, dati, datio 'gift of the hand'. 2) deh-lou-etic: dess 'rightside' + adj. louetic < *lom-etic 'handed' . 3) do-guo-lou-it gl. redegit 'administers, manages', i.e. 'handles'.  4) Dreh-(h)olom, personal name
In calonn armcriniat 'trembling of the heart' and in the personal name Uuin-calon.

Troim is the infinitive of a verb derived from Old Breton tro 'turn'. The meaning 'to turn' is present in the Middle and Modern Breton continuants of this verb as well as in the Welsh cognate troi 'to walk around, to turn'. Old Breton troim guar semms to mean 'to ininsist'. Further, troint, 3Pl. ind. pres. glosses residunt in (maria alta) rursus in se ipsa residunt, 'to return, to retire'.
carn gl. ungula caballi 'hoof of a horse'.
ladam, 1sg. indic. pres. gl. caedo 'I slay, I kill'.
Unclear, however, whether *ὄψ this is actually the regular term for 'eye' or is only found fossilised in compounds, as in Homeric and Classical Greek.

Infinitive gud-but < *guid-but with *guid < *PIE *u̯ei̯d- 'to see, to behold' (LIV² 665) and but < *butā- from *bʰu̯eh₂- 'to become, etc.' (LIV² 98f.). Only the infinitive is compounded, the finite forms are from *u̯ei̯d- alone: guid 3sg.pres.ind. 'knows', -goinomp 1pl. pres.ind. 'we know' (alternative analysis by Schumacher 2004, 693), gus impers. pres. ind. 'one knows'.
Not most basic term in this sense.
Seems to be quite rare and the meaning is sometimes specialied. Cf. however  an adcladat gl. aucupantes Ml. 112b2 . adcichlus gl. uenabor, Thes. ii 48.6. 362.z.
Seems to mean ʿmorally goodʿ; higly frequent in the texts, but probably not the normal term.
Only attested in Zor. Pahlavi, but existence in Manichaean very probable.
morphological analysis and connection with hitt. zaḫḫ-
Middle inflection καίομαι reflects intransitive use 'burn'.  Find in the standard lexica under the active καίω.
original root noun that underwent thematicization to hāssa- in Middle Hittite.
Does not appear to be the correct Swadesh term.
ɡeneral term for an amount of small particles
might be the unmarked term, but insecure.
Vasmer also has the AF kšeẃ.

The word is contextually is used in the prohibition of disturbing a ritual observation.  Untermann records a proposed interpretation 'sich (von der Stelle) entfernen, herumlaufen', but ultimately, as often is the case in the Wörterbuch, considers the true meaning of the verb to be 'unbekannt'.
The exact semantics are not precisely determined, but occurs on a fountain bowl (Brunnenschalen).  Untermann suggests a meaning of '(Leitungs)wasser' or 'Wasserleitung'.
Cites the noun OAv. viiānayā (Lok. Sg. n.) 'spirit(ness)'.
Cites *uysan- 'to breath[sic] out' as the LKh. form.
Contains detailed information about possible word formation.

Blažek (2010) also gives δίδω, but this word is archaising usage and not the Swadesh term (cf. Andriotis et al. 1999 s.v. δίδω).  δίνω is an analogical remodelling of older δίδω to other present-stems in -νω.

This is not the most neutral standard German term.
You might find it in medical contexts or maybe other technical forms; otherwise it is outdated.
http://www.duden.de/rechtschreibung/Bein says it was used for "bone" in Southern Germany, Switzerland and Austria which I don't know for sure.

The simple verb 'frieren' exists as well; however, I would say that it becomes replace by 'gefrieren'. - A Google search for 'Wasser friert' yielded about 6.730 results, for 'Wasser gefriert' about 29.000.
Another word which comes close in meaning is 'richtig'. But 'wahr' is more specifically reserved for factual accuracy, while 'richtig' may also designate something like propriety.
This adjective applies both for skin as well as surfaces of objects (pace the hint on German in the Wiki definition-justification for 'smooth' ).

'Kralle' may be used with reptiles, birds and mammals. Thus it has a wider range of application than 'Klaue' which in normal language use is preferably combined with predators (e.g. eagles) or animals that might potentially be dangerous for men, such as lions or bears. Therefore I take 'Kralle' to be the Swadesh term rather than 'Klaue'. - 'Klaue' is however kept as a synonym because this is a meaning that is not as frequently used as others in the list and thus distinctions get blurred more easily. Furthermore, 'Klaue' has cognates in other Germanic languages.

The compounded forms 'der hier' and 'der da' are superseding the older contrastive pair 'dieser' and 'jener', because distal 'jener' is increasingly uncommon in everyday speech.
The compounded forms 'der hier' and 'der da' or 'der dort' are superseding the older contrastive pair 'dieser' and 'jener', because distal 'jener' is increasingly uncommon in everyday speech.
I would say that 'der da' is not as exclusively 'distal' as 'der dort'. It thus seems to be the alternative that we are looking for.

I would say that 'jener' is nowadays only used in texts as an equivalent of 'the former', or in phrases such as 'in jenen Tagen'. In everyday use, for referring to distal objects 'der da' or 'der dort' are the standard forms.
Also cf. the passage in the Duden Grammatik.
'da' is less specific than 'dort'. 'da' may also indicate proximity. It is thus in meaning as well as in form the more basic term (dort < ahd. dar-ot).
A search in the DWDS corpus shows that Rinde is the more frequent term.
The meaning of the word is unclear.  Connection to the meaning 'woman' is based on an uncertain etymological comparison to Lat. uxōr 'wife'.

'Kralle' is an alternative form of Kral 'hook' which is already attested in OHG. 'Kralle' is attested only from the 16th century onwards. The EWA entry however assumes that it must be older because of MHG denominative verb erkrellen 'to take with the claws, to grab'. Either way, the lexeme appears only in German. It might possibly be traced back to the PIE root *ger- 'to turn, to twist, to wind'.

The contexts of this word are uncertain, but the consistent use of the determinative GIŠ indicates the word has something to do with wood.  It is argued that the word may be connected with the Sumerogram (GIŠ)TIR 'forest' that is sometimes phonetically complemented with a -šar/-šn- flexional ending, and so the translation 'forest' has commonly been adopted for this lexeme, although the evidence for this identification is admittedly circumstantial.  The possibility remains open that it might not be the Swadesh term.

S.v. parḫuwayaš or mašḫuwayaš gen. of a n.; (a creature whose meat was dried and eaten).  A more precise meaning is unclear.  parḫuwayaš or mašḫuwayaš (either reading is of the sign pár possible) is attested in a list of foodstuffs (KBo 10.33 + KBo 10.28 v 1-2).  In a similar list of foodstuffs (KBo 10.52:10), the Sumerogram MUŠEN.ḪI.A 'birds' is followed by the Sumerogram KU₆ḪI.A 'fishes', and on the basis of this textual parallel a meaning of 'fish' is sometimes postulated, but it is unclear whether this is the actual meaning of the lexeme.

Middle Persian nhwm(b)- may either belong to PIE ?*k̑eu̯bʰ- 'to be/become beautiful' > Proto-Iranian 2. *su(m)b/p- ? (Cheung 2007: 368), or to Proto-Iranian 1. *su(m)b/p 'to pierce, to bore' (Cheung loc. cit.). The latter solution would be best supported formally (stem formation).
A third possibility would be to relate Middle Persian nhwm(b)- to Albanian humb, aor. hup 'to lose', PIE root *(s)k̑eup- ?.
(summary by Cassandra Freiberg based on an e-mail exchange with Martin Kümmel, 29.05.2016)

The form 'hurniyaz' is inherited from the Ringe et al. 2002 wordlist used in IELex. I am assuming that this would be an -nt- participle with passive meaning, formed to the verb ḫa/urnai- 'to sprinkle, to drip'; thus the intended meaning would be *'sprinkled' > 'wet'. Unfortunately, this form does not exist in HW² Ḫ (cf. s.v. ḫarnai-, ḫarniya-, pp.315-316), nor does is it listed in Kloekhorst EDHIL (cf. s.v. ḫarna-/ḫarn-, pp.308-309), nor is it to be found in Puhvel HED H (cf. s.v. hurnai-, hurniya-). As far as I have been able to ascertain, this participial form with the meaning 'wet' does not actually exist. It is not clear to me, at least, whether the unattested participle of ḫarnai- 'to sprinkle', would have actually meant 'wet'. Consequently, I have marked this lexeme as non-Swadesh.

Meaning in context is far from assured, only based on the not really clear Pahlavi translation with "rōdagān". The word is given as a source of noise and an alternative between 'water' and some criminals.
Thus it is doubtful if this is the main Avestan word for 'river'. Other candidates are not less often attested, e.g. θraōtah- (in a compound) or dānu- which is attested twice: once as such and once in a compound.
